            <section class="prose">
              <h2>How this database sizing calculator works</h2>
              <p>
                This tool gives you a practical, engine-agnostic estimate of how
                much storage your database will need today and in the future. It
                is inspired by vendor guides from SQL Server, Oracle, and
                others, but simplified so you can use it for any relational
                database.
              </p>

              <h3>1. Data size per table</h3>
              <p>For each table, we estimate data size as:</p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p>
                  <strong>Data size (bytes)</strong> =
                  <code>row_count × avg_row_size_bytes</code>
                </p>
              </div>
              <p>
                You provide the current row count and an average row size in
                bytes. If you do not know the exact row size, you can:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  Approximate based on column definitions (e.g.,
                  <code>INT = 4 bytes</code>, <code>BIGINT = 8</code>,
                  <code>DATETIME = 8</code>, <code>VARCHAR(100) ≈ 50</code> on
                  average).
                </li>
                <li>
                  Measure a sample table in a test database and divide total
                  size by row count.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h3>2. Index overhead</h3>
              <p>
                Indexes often consume as much or more space than the base table,
                especially in OLTP systems with many nonclustered indexes.
                Instead of modeling each index individually, we use a
                configurable percentage:
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p>
                  <strong>Index size</strong> =
                  <code>data_size × (index_overhead_percent / 100)</code>
                </p>
              </div>
              <p>Typical values:</p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>OLTP / transactional:</strong> 50–100% of data size.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Data warehouse:</strong> 20–60% (fewer, wider indexes,
                  more compression).
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Logging / telemetry:</strong> 10–40% (few indexes,
                  mostly append-only).
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h3>3. Transaction log space</h3>
              <p>
                Transaction log requirements depend on workload, recovery model,
                and backup frequency. For capacity planning, we use a simple
                factor:
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p>
                  <strong>Log space</strong> =
                  <code>data_size × log_factor</code>
                </p>
              </div>
              <p>
                For example, a factor of <code>0.3</code> means log space is
                estimated at 30% of data size. For heavy write workloads or long
                log backup intervals, use a higher factor.
              </p>

              <h3>4. Backup storage</h3>
              <p>
                Backup storage is estimated from the total database size (data +
                indexes + log) and your retention policy:
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p>
                  <strong>Backup size per full backup</strong> =
                  <code>(data + index + log) × compression_factor</code>
                </p>
                <p>
                  <strong>Backups on disk</strong> =
                  <code
                    >backup_size_per_full × (retention_days /
                    backup_interval_days)</code
                  >
                </p>
              </div>
              <p>
                This calculator assumes one full backup per day and uses the
                <strong>compression factor</strong> you provide (for example,
                0.5 for 50% compression).
              </p>

              <h3>5. Growth over time</h3>
              <p>
                For each table, you can specify an
                <strong>annual growth in rows</strong>. We project row counts at
                the planning horizon:
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p>
                  <strong>Rows at horizon</strong> =
                  <code>current_rows + annual_growth × years</code>
                </p>
                <p>
                  <strong>Data at horizon</strong> =
                  <code>rows_at_horizon × avg_row_size_bytes</code>
                </p>
              </div>
              <p>
                Index, log, and backup sizes at the horizon are then recomputed
                from the projected data size.
              </p>

              <h3>6. Safety margin</h3>
              <p>
                Real systems rarely behave exactly like our assumptions. To
                avoid under-provisioning, you can add a
                <strong>safety margin</strong>:
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p>
                  <strong>Total with margin</strong> =
                  <code>total_size × (1 + safety_margin_percent / 100)</code>
                </p>
              </div>
              <p>
                For production systems, a margin of 20–50% is common, depending
                on how often you can scale storage.
              </p>

              <h2>Practical tips for database capacity planning</h2>

              <h3>Start from workload, not just schema</h3>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  Identify <strong>hot tables</strong> that grow fastest
                  (orders, events, logs, audit tables).
                </li>
                <li>
                  Estimate <strong>daily inserts</strong>, updates, and deletes
                  for each major table.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Consider <strong>retention policies</strong> (e.g., purge logs
                  older than 90 days).
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h3>Account for engine-specific features</h3>
              <p>While this calculator is engine-agnostic, keep in mind:</p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>SQL Server:</strong> page size (8 KB), row-overflow
                  storage, clustered vs nonclustered indexes, compression
                  (ROW/PAGE).
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Oracle:</strong> block size, tablespaces, segment
                  overhead, automatic segment space management.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>PostgreSQL:</strong> MVCC bloat, autovacuum
                  efficiency, TOAST tables for large values.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>MySQL/InnoDB:</strong> file-per-table vs shared
                  tablespace, redo/undo logs, row format (COMPACT, DYNAMIC).
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h3>Include non-database storage</h3>
              <p>
                Total storage for a database platform is usually larger than the
                database files alone:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>OS and binaries.</li>
                <li>TempDB / temporary tablespaces.</li>
                <li>Staging tables, ETL landing zones.</li>
                <li>Monitoring, audit, and job history tables.</li>
              </ul>

              <h3>Iterate with real measurements</h3>
              <p>After deployment, compare actual sizes with your estimates:</p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  Capture <strong>data and index size per table</strong> from
                  system catalogs.
                </li>
                <li>Measure <strong>daily growth</strong> over a few weeks.</li>
                <li>
                  Update your assumptions in this calculator and re-run the
                  sizing.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h2>FAQ</h2>

              <h3>Is this calculator suitable for cloud databases?</h3>
              <p>
                Yes. You can use it to size <strong>Azure SQL Database</strong>,
                <strong>Amazon RDS/Aurora</strong>,
                <strong>Google Cloud SQL</strong>, and other managed services.
                Once you have the estimated total size, map it to the closest
                storage tier or instance class offered by your cloud provider.
              </p>

              <h3>How do I estimate average row size?</h3>
              <p>A quick approach is:</p>
              <ol>
                <li>List all columns and their data types.</li>
                <li>
                  Use typical byte sizes (e.g., <code>INT = 4</code>,
                  <code>BIGINT = 8</code>, <code>DATETIME = 8</code>,
                  <code>DECIMAL(18,2) ≈ 9</code>).
                </li>
                <li>
                  For variable-length types (<code>VARCHAR</code>,
                  <code>NVARCHAR</code>), assume an average usage (e.g., 30–50%
                  of max length).
                </li>
                <li>
                  Add 10–20% overhead for row headers, alignment, and nullable
                  columns.
                </li>
              </ol>

              <h3>How often should I revisit my database sizing?</h3>
              <p>
                For rapidly growing systems, review sizing monthly or quarterly.
                For stable line-of-business applications, twice a year may be
                enough. Any major feature change that adds new tables or
                significantly increases traffic should trigger a new sizing
                exercise.
              </p>
